The European « Green Deal »
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The « Green Deal for Europe » announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a landmark for the entire world – a guide for the transformation toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is: a display at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets and diplomacy, a large number of topics involved and related, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined according to objectives set on a schedule, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a "farm to table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat products overly processed by industry, nor kills the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on citizens themselves.
Once again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere hot air.
But go tell the French president Emmanuel Macron, who has faced more than a year of demonstrations turning into riots, or the Chilean president Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices, that these are useless chatter.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but afterwards.
Adherents of neoliberalism in the United States will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means enduring elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent train connections, highways with lanes in such poor condition that they can't be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each cycle of American elections now costs 8 billion dollars, or even more, and the funding comes from billionaires, from major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the health care industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect at all costs the status quo.
The solutions provided by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences emanating from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be, and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not narrowly partisan).
A mixed economy, which combines markets, the state's regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have good reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economy in transport or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, move towards a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But for this, we must overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining, and other public assistance.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly regarding new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, renewal of industrial equipment, etc. The financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to the ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, whereas China's share rises to 30% and that of the United States to 14%.
Even if Europe succeeds in implementing its Green Deal in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its struggle.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest emitter of CO2 (although its emissions per capita remain two times lower than those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, under pressure from the United States, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead offers this country a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and feasible plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
